segments.text: praise and changes and so forth.
You mentioned as key positive decisions to admit women and racial integration, non-compulsory core, broaden more graduate programs and so forth.
Let's continue to talk about any advice that you would offer to anyone today who's looking toward the future.
of how to make A&M even better.
I think we've got to get a handle on some things.
Hazing, for instance, I think it's got to be wiped out.
got to try to erase the lingering image of a college, which I'm afraid still exists to some degree.
During your days as faculty member, were you aware of much hazing going on?
It crept up, yes.
Yes, I realized it did occur.
Did students ever, freshmen particularly, come to your office and share with you their feelings about being in the Corps?
It's rather strange, I think.
I had a few who would come, close the door, burst into tears, say, I like A&M, but I don't like the Corps, and so therefore I'm going to have to leave because the Corps is just not for me.
Let's see.
Trying to make an answer.
What should A&M aspire to be today?
Should it aspire to be one of the key top public institutions in the country?
Yes, I think it should.
You mentioned fine arts as an area to be added.
Do you think of any other academic areas that you think A&M ought to add?
No, I don't believe so.
The last I knew, we could not qualify for a 5A chapter.
Is that still true?
I don't know.

I was, back in the 70s, I was part of the group that welcomed, and we had been set up because the three visitors were spinster women from comparatively small Eastern all-female institutions, and they had been fed information that led them to believe that every one of us was a hard-nosed male chauvinist so-and-so.
And I can't help but believe that we deserve Phi Beta Kappa as well as Baylor or TCU or Trinity.
I'm not at all knocking them.
But I think we have the quality to equal those.
But I wish we could do that because I think that would be a very good signal.
I think the addition of the fine arts would help that a great deal.
Matter of fact, Paul Parrish in the English department
is working on that very thing.
Well, not 5-8.
He's trying to work out a fine arts program, a combination of theater and music.
All right, let's see.
We're getting close to the end.
Do you have any Aggie stories, whether they be true or not,
Aggie stories that you enjoy passing on?
Well, I've been thinking about that, but I haven't come up with any.
I came up with some faculty member stories.
Well, those are good.

Well, one that a couple of them used to be involved, the same person we had, a young fellow, came in 1946, just graduated from the University of Illinois, named Dude Huck, and Abel Huck, Abel Dude Huck,
How do you spell Hubka?
H-U-B-K-A.
And Dr. Mayo was very fond of him.
He treated him like a son, both from the affection end and the raving mouth end when he needed it, but he was a real pricey little rascal.
At any rate, they invited us over for dinner one night, so when we got there, his wife, me, and then
big pot of boiling water on the stove, and Dude was out with his shotgun, going to shoot the game for the entree.
He came back with a dove and a woodpecker.
I'm sure they had other things, but the entree, Martin and I each got a bite of dove, and Dude and his wife shared the woodpecker.
Another story on the same guy.
He was teaching a sophomore literature class in our English 203, and he was teaching the play that's based on the Sacco-Vanzetti case.
The name of the play escapes me at the moment, but at any rate, that's what he was teaching.
Well, also in the department was Colonel Kane, a very urbane, sophisticated, articulate, retired army man, and he made a study of the Sacco-Vanzetti case,
So, Lepke invited him to come talk to the class about it.
So, when they got there, he said, this was Colonel Kane, he's a retired military, and he's made a study of the Sacro Donzetti case.
Sure, this will be a very interesting talk.
I wish I could stay to hear it.
Took off.
Then there was, in that same 46, there was an old gentleman named Mr. Childs,
And we were all hired sight unseen.
They were desperate to meet those classes with the veterans flocking in.
Anyway, Mr. Childs came with good credentials, but he wasn't too far off.
We were at some gathering.
He discovered that Frank Pierce was a speech teacher.
He was talking to him.
He said, do you know the work of Robinson?
I said, no, I don't believe I do.
All the rest of the evening, Mr. Childs went around by there, teach his speech, doesn't know Robinson.
Teach his speech, doesn't know Robinson.
Well, Frank went to him at the end of the, he said, Mr. Childs, he said, tell me who this Robinson is.
He said, if somebody I should know, I wouldn't know.
Childs said, Robinson?
Robinson?
I don't know any Robinson.
Did any student or anyone ever tease you about being from Illinois, not being local, not being a Texan?
Oh, yes.
Oh, yeah.
I got that.
I get called a Yankee every now and then.
I remember one early teacher evaluation.
I don't know actually what the student meant.
He said he wants to impress his Yankee ideas.
Did they ever think?
indicate they thought you were liberal or conservative or anything like that?
Oh yeah, we had a few essays here and there that touched upon liberal issues.
I think they can see that I endorsed them more or less.
Let's see, any sad, poignant stories, recollections, experiences?
Oh, well, we had deaths in our department.
We had two young men, obviously, people killed and all that kind of stuff.
Kirkus Little was one of them.
How did the department handle that?
Well, everybody grieved, of course, and we contacted their families and flowers to the funeral.
The things you do was rather devastating to us.
The other young man was killed on Labor Day at Plannersville.
He had a convention with a number of students.
It was a big shock for them.
As a matter of fact, I come to think about it, I didn't.
Those students didn't come to talk to me.
I did what I could to try to get the man away.
Now, were you and the women in your life, were you all Presbyterians early on here?
Here we were, I grew up a Baptist, and when we went to my first teaching job, we went from town, which there was no Baptist church, probably wouldn't have sampled it had there been.
So I went with Margaret and fell in love with the church.
When you moved here, which church did you join?
We went to, we joined in Pride.
It was much closer to, see, we were at the field.
It was much closer, and we liked it very much.
In the late 40s, early 50s, what was the relationship between Bryan and College Station?
When y'all first moved here, there wasn't a good grocery store in College Station.
Where'd y'all do your shopping?
Well, we went to Bryan.
Actually, there were a couple of stores.
There was Charlie's at the North Gate, and Manning Smith had a grocery store over there.
There was something called the Knife Depot and travel agencies off of Walton.
And I might have met that grocery store there.
What was there right here to the north and west toward the railroad on Jersey?
Was Maidly's Pharmacy there yet?
Yeah, Maidly's was there, yeah.
For those that don't remember, Maidly's described that.
Well, yeah.
It was a good old-fashioned drugstore that had all the stuff.
It was sort of fun and served sandwiches.
A lot of people dropped in there for lunch.
Everybody knew Mr.
Badly to hang out for the kids.
Let the kids come in after school and drink their folks and sit around and talk.
It was quite an institution which a lot of us still miss.
What else was there along there?
I believe Brewers was, and maybe the Cleaners.
No alcohol in Brazos County then?
Went across Whiskey Bridge.
And that went way back, didn't it?
Yes.
Did you and your family have any interaction with the students living in the project houses?
No, the project houses
We were sort of on our way out, I believe, if I recall correctly, but we did not have.
Let's see, we talked about coaches.

Okay, let's, as we're really getting close to the end, let's make believe that someone walks up to you now and gives you a check worth at least hundreds of thousands of dollars, if not more than that,
And the only restriction to that gift is you must pass it on to Texas A&M, but you can decide the use or uses to which that money would be put.
What would you give, if you had lots of money to give away to A&M, what would you give it for?
What are your pet projects?
The strange thing to be dumb and saddled about is, well, certainly not bricks and mortar.
I certainly think I'd be interested in giving the library some additional help, and I think that I would probably want to give some of it to the College of Liberal Arts.
Is there any special subject area in the library?
I really don't know what the status of that collection is, but that would be a special area depending on what they found that really needed or what they asked for.
I might want to do something for Opus.
Possibly the Memorial Student Center.
I certainly want to direct all of it where it benefits people.
I suppose what I actually would do is do some research.
Find out where needs are and what some of those areas actually want and actually need.

right let me conclude then by thanking you very much and by reminding you if you have any papers personal papers reminiscences or any sort about the A&M years that you'd be willing for the archives to copy please do so because we need as many actual
personal items as possible.
Well actually I've pretty well read that stuff.

Say that what I wish more than anything else would be the letters that students wrote home because there they were usually very confidential and very honest about what was happening and who was helping them.
I had to vacate my office a short time ago.
That was quite a job.
I gave most of them to the graduate students.
I just put them out and have them.
I brought home my collections, you know, my full set of Google tickets.
I gave the full set of Twain to my daughter.
Good.
Well, let me thank you very much.
What is that?
